    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-29T20:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-29T20:40:00-05:00" n="321"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d321">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.00/1355.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Sullivan</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Santo Domingo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-29T21:00:00-04:40">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 29, 1914, 9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In answer to my inquiry Dominican Government states that elections are complete
                    in five provinces. In four provinces primary <pb facs="0358" n="242"
                        xml:id="pg_242"/> elections are complete but not secondary. No elections in
                    three provinces. Government admits probability of postponement in elections of
                    the President and convening Congress. Dominican Government asserts that
                    supplementary elections will bring proceedings into conformity with
                    constitutional rights. Opposition maintains that Government loses mandate after
                    July 1st. Foreign representatives asking what attitude American Government will
                    take. Please instruct. No immediate probability of Government losing de facto
                    power.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sullivan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
